    "body_en": "<p>The Smile mission is set to launch on a Vega-C rocket from Europe’s Spaceport in French Guiana on Thursday 9 April at 08: 29 CEST/07: 29 BST/03: 29 local time. Follow along as we communicate on the final preparations for launch. The institutional report frames the development in practical terms and ties it to the broader mission or observing effort.</p><p>That matters because astronomy advances when separate observations start pointing in the same direction. The Smile mission is set to launch on a Vega-C rocket from Europe’s Spaceport in French Guiana on Thursday 9 April at 08: 29 CEST/07: 29 BST/03: 29 local time. Follow along as we communicate on the final preparations for launch.</p><p>Journalists are invited to join online media briefings in English, French, Spanish, Italian and German.</p><p>What gives the story weight is not just the object itself, but the way the measurement trims the range of plausible explanations. Journalists are invited to join online media briefings in English, French, Spanish, Italian and German.</p><p>Because the account comes from ESA Space Science, it works best as a primary institutional report close to the data and operations, not as the final word on scientific validation.</p><p>The next step is to see whether other instruments and other wavelengths tell the same story.</p><p class=\"art-source\"><a href=\"https://www.esa.int/Science_Exploration/Space_Science/Smile/T-20_days_Smile_to_launch_on_9_April\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Source</a></p>",
