    "body_en": "<p>A Mississippi State physicist has produced a direct laboratory measurement of a key nuclear reaction believed to occur during explosive bursts on neutron stars. These bursts forge heavier elements, the building blocks of planets and life. The institutional report frames the development in practical terms and ties it to the broader mission or observing effort.</p><p>That matters because astrophysics becomes persuasive when an observed signal can be tied to a defensible physical explanation. Edited by Stephanie Baum, reviewed by Robert Egan This article has been reviewed according to Science X&#x27;s editorial process and policies. Editors have highlighted the following attributes while ensuring the content&#x27;s credibility: Add as preferred source 56 Ni with (blue) and without (red) H 2 target at E c. m.</p><p>10. 3847/1538-4357/ae3de6&quot;&gt; The excitation energy spectrum of 56 Ni with (blue) and without (red) H 2 target at E c. m. 4. 0 ± 0. 4 MeV (upper) and 4. 68 ± 0. 25 MeV (lower panel), respectively.</p><p>The Astrophysical Journal (2026). 10. 3847/1538-4357/ae3de6 A Mississippi State physicist has produced a direct laboratory measurement of a key nuclear reaction believed to occur during explosive bursts on.</p><p>The broader interest lies in turning an observational clue into something that can be weighed against competing models. Every heavier element, from the oxygen we breathe to the iron in Earth&#x27;s core, was forged later in stars and stellar explosions.</p><p>Because the account comes from Phys.org Space, it works best as a primary institutional report close to the data and operations, not as the final word on scientific validation.</p><p>The next step is to see whether independent datasets and physical modeling converge on the same interpretation.</p><p class=\"art-source\"><a href=\"https://phys.org/news/2026-03-physicist-recreates-neutron-star-reaction.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Source</a></p>",
